ladders.explanation:
This sub-routine is the core of the sorting approach, responsible for inserting a single element into a temporary stack that is already sorted in descending order (largest at bottom). The intuition is that we can recursively compare the element with the top of the temporary stack: if the element is larger or equal to the top, we push it directly because it maintains the sorted order; otherwise, we pop the top element, recursively insert the new element deeper into the stack, then push the popped element back on top. This works because the temporary stack is always kept sorted, and recursion allows us to 'make space' for smaller elements by temporarily removing larger ones. The step-by-step algorithm: 1. Base case: if temporary stack is empty OR element >= top of temporary stack, push element and return. 2. Otherwise, pop the top element from temporary stack, recursively call insert_sorted with the same element, then push the popped element back. Time complexity is O(n) per insertion in worst case (when element is smallest and needs to be placed at bottom), and space is O(n) for recursion depth. This feeds into the full problem by being called for each element popped from the original stack. Common mistakes include forgetting to push back the popped element after recursion or incorrect comparison operators. The real pattern is a recursive function that maintains stack sortedness through conditional pushes and temporary pops.

Pseudocode:
def insert_sorted(temp_stack, element):
    if temp_stack is empty or element >= temp_stack.top():
        temp_stack.push(element)
    else:
        top = temp_stack.pop()
        insert_sorted(temp_stack, element)
        temp_stack.push(top)
